      <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">About Our Unit Converters</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">xConvert24 provides 25 free unit converters that cover every common measurement need. Each converter is designed for speed and accuracy — enter a value, select your units, and get the result instantly. There is no page reload, no waiting for a server response, and no sign-up required. Whether you are a student working on physics homework, a chef adapting an American recipe to metric measurements, a traveller comparing fuel economy standards, or an engineer calculating pressure differentials, we have you covered.</p>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">How Our Converters Work</h3>
      <p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Every converter on xConvert24 performs calculations client-side in your browser using standard conversion factors. This means your data never leaves your device — there is no server processing, no API calls for basic conversions, and no risk of your sensitive measurements being logged anywhere. The only exception is the currency converter, which fetches live exchange rates from a public API to ensure you get the most up-to-date rates available.</p>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Metric vs Imperial: A Global Challenge</h3>
      <p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">The world uses two primary measurement systems: the International System of Units (SI, commonly called metric) and the imperial/US customary system. Only three countries — the United States, Liberia, and Myanmar — have not officially adopted the metric system as their primary standard. This creates a constant need for conversion in international trade, travel, cooking, engineering, and everyday communication. Our converters bridge this gap effortlessly, supporting both systems across every measurement category.</p>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Categories Explained</h3>
      <p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">The <strong>Most Popular</strong> section includes the six converters used most frequently by our visitors: weight (kilograms to pounds is the single most common conversion worldwide), length (metres to feet), temperature (Celsius to Fahrenheit), currency (with live rates), speed, and volume. These cover roughly 80 percent of all conversion needs.</p>
      <p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">The <strong>Science and Engineering</strong> section handles professional-grade conversions: pressure for HVAC technicians and meteorologists, energy for physicists and nutritionists (joules to calories), power for electrical engineers, frequency for radio and electronics work, angles for surveyors and game developers, and data storage for IT professionals comparing storage capacities and transfer speeds.</p>
      <p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">The <strong>Everyday and Lifestyle</strong> section focuses on practical daily needs. The cooking converter helps home cooks translate American cup measurements into millilitres. The oven temperature converter handles the perennial Celsius-to-gas-mark question for British baking. Clothing and shoe size converters are essential for international online shopping where sizing standards differ between the US, UK, EU, and Asian markets. The fuel economy converter helps drivers compare vehicles rated in different standards (mpg vs l/100km).</p>
      <p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">The <strong>Specialist</strong> section includes niche converters for specific fields: precious metals for jewellers and investors who need troy ounce conversions, number base conversions for programmers working with binary and hexadecimal, Roman numerals for historians and students, and body composition calculations for fitness professionals.</p>
      <p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">The <strong>Sports and Fitness</strong> section helps athletes and coaches convert between pace and speed formats used in different regions. Runners in the UK think in min/mile while European runners use min/km — our running pace calculator converts seamlessly between them and estimates race times for 5K, 10K, half marathon, and full marathon distances.</p>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Accuracy and Precision</h3>
      <p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">All conversion factors used in our tools follow internationally recognised standards published by organisations like NIST (National Institute of Standards and Technology), ISO, and the BIPM (Bureau International des Poids et Mesures). Results are displayed to a precision appropriate for the measurement type — typically 4 to 6 significant figures. For scientific work requiring higher precision, the exact conversion factors are documented in the formula section of each converter.</p>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Looking for Calculators and Other Tools?</h3>
      <p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">If you need calculators (BMI, loan, scientific), time tools (world clock, timezone converter, stopwatch), creative tools (color picker, image editor), or security utilities (password generator), visit our <a href="/tools" class="text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 hover:underline font-medium">Tools</a> directory. We also have a dedicated <a href="/tools/timezone" class="text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 hover:underline font-medium">Timezone Converter</a> for scheduling across regions with full daylight saving time support.</p>
